{"timestamp":"00:09:17.337","source":"Browser","level":"ERROR","message":"The final argument passed to %s changed size between renders. The order and size of this array must remain constant.\n\nPrevious: %s\nIncoming: %s useEffect [16, Every chess player remembers painful losses. A winning position thrown away, a simple tactic overlooked, or a brilliant idea refuted instantly by the opponent. At first, defeats feel discouraging, but over time you realize they are the most honest teachers in chess.\r\nWins often hide mistakes. You may play inaccurately and still succeed because your opponent blunders. Losses, however, expose weaknesses clearly. They show gaps in calculation, positional understanding, or emotional control. Reviewing lost games can reveal patterns — recurring mistakes that limit improvement.\r\nStrong players develop a healthy relationship with losing. Instead of avoiding it, they analyze it. Each defeat becomes data, not failure. The board does not judge; it simply reflects reality. Improvement begins the moment a player becomes curious about their mistakes rather than frustrated by them., Learning Through Defeat] [16, Every chess player remembers painful losses. A winning position thrown away, a simple tactic overlooked, or a brilliant idea refuted instantly by the opponent. At first, defeats feel discouraging, but over time you realize they are the most honest teachers in chess.\r\nWins often hide mistakes. You may play inaccurately and still succeed because your opponent blunders. Losses, however, expose weaknesses clearly. They show gaps in calculation, positional understanding, or emotional control. Reviewing lost games can reveal patterns — recurring mistakes that limit improvement.\r\nStrong players develop a healthy relationship with losing. Instead of avoiding it, they analyze it. Each defeat becomes data, not failure. The board does not judge; it simply reflects reality. Improvement begins the moment a player becomes curious about their mist